{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"16fb67bc-b495-46e4-a664-366239d2edd2","content":"In .NET MAUI, you configure platform lifecycle event mappings in your `MauiProgram.cs` using `ConfigureLifecycleEvents`:\n\n```csharp\nusing Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents;\n\nbuilder.ConfigureLifecycleEvents(events =>\n{\n#if ANDROID\n    events.AddAndroid(android => android\n        .OnPause(activity => { /* runs on Android pause */ })\n        .OnStop(activity => { /* runs on Android stop */ }));\n#elif IOS\n    events.AddiOS(ios => ios\n        .DidEnterBackground(app => { /* runs on iOS background */ }));\n#endif\n});\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- Add the `Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents` namespace.\n- Use `#if ANDROID` / `#elif IOS` preprocessor directives to keep platform code separated.\n- Each handler receives the native object (`Activity` on Android, `UIApplication` on iOS), so you can call native APIs directly.\n- Other events are available too — `OnResume`, `WillTerminate`, `OnCreate`, etc.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"d4fe71be-8dfd-4e00-8138-3937c65d268f","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to hook into platform-specific lifecycle events in .NET MAUI — specifically Android's OnPause/OnStop and iOS's DidEnterBackground. This is a knowledge question, not a code task, so I can answer directly.","outputTokens":343,"requestId":"B7D9:3A1214:1312BC:192336:69FFD7FF"},"id":"bd44ad3f-9a4a-438d-becc-a60c9382a0b7","timestamp":"2026-05-10T00:57:43.467Z","parentId":"3bd9ea98-d15e-41e0-8db3-ffc07f243843"}
